,Recommended,457960,30989222,Posted: 6 April,all,Isaac_HoZ,"For a more in-depth look (and some high level gameplay) check out my video review:https://youtu.be/bRgVU7zyuXEHolopoint is like if SuperHot had sex with Space Pirate Simulator and Geometry Wars is in the closet watching… but there is no slow motion and you can only use a bow and arrow. Is that helpful? I think that describes this game pretty well after playing it for 50+ hours. At its heart it’s another wave based survival game that strongly prioritizes your own reactive movements above all else. Yes, it’s important to be accurate but you can miss an arrow here and there without the game ending. You yourself can only take two hits until it’s Game Over, so getting the Hell out of the way is a bit more important than landing your shots. That being said, I’d try to make every arrow count anyway as that’s pretty key for your hitting a new high score.Chasing after your high score is very addictive as no matter how low your score starts there is just something about knowing you’re a faster and a better virtual bowman than the dude you just toppled on the leaderboard. There is a downside: good luck not tangling your Vive’s cable. No, seriously, good luck. You’re going to need it. Based on how often enemies attack you from behind it would be a damn miracle for your not to have a horrifically tangled mess by the time you’re done with an intense play session.Still, even with that negative, I’d urge you to buy Holopoint if any of this sounds vaguely interesting. It may not be the best bow and arrow simulator on the Vive (though I intend to find out what is) but it sure does make you feel like a badass… perhaps more than any other game before it. I’d just probably do some stretches or something beforehand though, you don’t want to pull a hammy."
