,Recommended,457960,31438109,Posted: 29 April,all,balthazar,"A year and a bit on this is still one of my favourite VR games. The mechanics are simple; shoot a box and it explodes and shoots a projectile back at you, which you have to dodge (in later levels, samurai also steadily approach you and you have to shoot them before they get to you). Simple though they may be, they're tuned perfectly. You're always focusing on the next target, balancing the time to line up a shot with the urgency of the two boxes behind you that you can hear are getting ready to explode (boxes left un-shot will explode and shoot at you of their own volition: still dodge-able but much harder and less predictable).The sound design is also excellent. As boxes near their exploding point, they make an unintrusive whooshing sound that builds to a crescendo. This is both long enough and balanced enough that you know exactly how long you have. It's also very well placed in the space around you, so you know what direction it's in. Excellent soundtrack as well.The game is very physical. It is the only VR game I've come across that actually builds up a sweat. By some accounts the game can be cheesed a bit if you're methodical with dodges, but it's equivalent to using a dictionary in scrabble; it may give better results, but it's no fun. It's best played leaping and spinning around like a ninja. Treat it that way and it will entirely fulfil your Matrix fantasies.I always see it reccommended for new users but rarely evangalised, which I think is a crying shame. I think it's one of the most mechanically complete games available for VR.10/10 would arrow-ninja again.N.B. There's two different aiming mechanics. I highly reccommend switching it to 'two-handed', as this aims like a real bow (straight line from rear hand to front hand). The default mode uses the orientation of your front hand to aim and doesn't feel natural; your hand won't be where the string is. Any negative comparisons to archery in The Lab etc have probably not enabled this, as it makes the aiming systems identical. Wish it was the default though."
