,Recommended,457960,22537978,"Posted: 20 April, 2016",all,Malactus,"While Holopoints look alot of rudamentary compared to similar titles, such as Space pirate simulator; SPT is a light warmup compared to what you will encounter in Holopoint.You starting with shooting at cubes... Sounds boring right? Not as simple as it sounds. The moment you hit one, it retaliates and shoots back as they shatter. And if you leave them around for too long... they also shoot. This goes on with every increasing amounts and eventually you simply cannot hit them all before one shoots without you hitting it first... and thats when things change radically and new types of enemies start relentlessly be thrown, a suprise after another. And no, there are no shields, so no turtleing, and you have to dodge all the projectiles.Thats when things get really interesting and accuracy becomes very important.And its not just Point and shoot, you have to use both your hands to align your shots at your target, and coordinate with the other to reach the quever. You will feel even more bad *** when you manage to hit multiple targets in a row.I highly recommend this to anyone that the space to go side to side in, and has the physical fitness to play it: but do pull off some practise on turning with the head set on. There is a danger of getting tangled with the headset if one keeps turning a single direction. The game is really intense, and at its price, fully worth it.My current feedback:- It could use more variation in the music played back,- Arrows do not seem to be able to be used as a thrusting meelee weapon.- Could use a vibration queue indicating that an arrow has been grabbed from the quever- What is the indication of what health is remaining for player?"
